ological_challenge_of_self_tracking_data">Between digital traces and documentary analysis: the methodological challenge of self-tracking data</a><div class="ds-related-work--metadata"><a class="js-wsj-grid-card-author ds2-5-body-sm ds2-5-body-link" data-author-id="192932993" href="https://unimib-it.academia.edu/LauraArosio">Laura Arosio</a></div><p class="ds-related-work--metadata ds2-5-body-xs">DOAJ (DOAJ: Directory of Open Access Journals), 2021</p><p class="ds2-5-body-sm ds-related-work--abstract ">Trace analysis is a particular form of non-participant observation. It studies the physical and digital &amp;amp;quot;footprints&amp;amp;quot; left by individuals in the environments where they live. In this paper I use the classic and more restrictive definition of trace analysis and focus on intentionality as a feature that marks a boundary between trace analysis and other research methods. By doing this, I stress out the situationality and contextuality of (digital) data&amp;amp;#39;s meaning. I use an example involving digital data collected by individuals through mobile and wearable devices. The focus is on running routes mapped out using activity tracking apps. What happens when &amp;amp;quot;traces&amp;amp;quot; are intentionally created by users and shared with other people through social networks? What is the methodological challenge proposed by self-tracking measures when people attribute them a communicative intent? What is the boundary between trace analysis and documentary analysis?</p><div class="ds-related-work--ctas"><a class="ds2-5-text-link ds2-5-text-link--inline js-tc-loswp--wsj-grid-card-download-pdf-modal js-login-button--e8574e1e"><span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">download</span><span class="ds2-5-text-link__content">Download free PDF</span></a><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
