});</script><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => { const loginButton = document.querySelector('.js-login-button--49399697'); if (!loginButton) { throw new Error('Login button not found'); } const options = { detail: {"postLoginRedirectUrl":"https://www.academia.edu/37774665/BEING_IN_A_MEDIATED_WORLD_self_tracking_and_the_mind_body_environment","clickTrackingContext":{"source":"loswp--wsj-grid-card-download-pdf-modal","bucket":"outline","entity_id":37774665,"extra":{"source_work_id":37774665}},"configuredText":{"buttonsPage":{"header":"Read your PDF for free"},"emailEntryPage":{"subheader":"Sign up or log in to continue reading."},"emailLoginPage":{"subheader":"Log in to continue reading."},"emailRegistrationPage":{"subheader":"Sign up to continue reading."}},"registrationParams":{"user_source":"download","doc_id":57770516}} }; loginButton.addEventListener('click', () => { document.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent('open-login-modal', options)); }); });</script><a class="ds2-5-text-link ds2-5-text-link--inline js-wsj-grid-card-view-pdf" href="https://www.academia.edu/37774665/BEING_IN_A_MEDIATED_WORLD_self_tracking_and_the_mind_body_environment"><span class="ds2-5-text-link__content">View PDF</span><span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">chevron_right</span></a></div></div><div class="ds-related-work--container js-wsj-grid-card js-safe-related-work-wsj " data-collection-position="4" data-entity-id="34394786" data-sort-order="default"><a class="ds-related-work--title js-wsj-grid-card-title ds2-5-body-md ds2-5-body-link" href="https://www.academia.edu/34394786/The_Translucent_Self_How_Self_Tracking_Technologies_move_from_Technologies_of_the_Self_to_Technologies_for_the_Other">The Translucent Self: How Self-Tracking Technologies move from Technologies of the Self to Technologies for the Other</a><div class="ds-related-work--metadata"><a class="js-wsj-grid-card-author ds2-5-body-sm ds2-5-body-link" data-author-id="39142473" href="https://independent.academia.edu/GeraldMunters">Gerald  Munters</a></div><p class="ds2-5-body-sm ds-related-work--abstract ">This paper critically assesses the discourse around the Quantified Self movement and self-tracking technologies. In particular, the author focuses on how self-tracking technologies and the accumulated data about the self can be positioned as technologies of the self, e.g. by revealing information about the self such that one can change one&#39;s behaviour, and technologies for the other, technologies that demand one to view the self through the eyes of a third party to adhere to a norm. The self-tracking technologies and the gathering and sharing of information appear to have blurred the boundaries between the self, the technologies of self-tracking, and other users and developers. On the one hand, the other users are seen as positive entities that support the development of the self, whereas on the other hand, other users are seen as opposing entities that normalize and subject the self through surveillance. The author argues that self-tracking technologies can provide insights into aspect of oneself and strengthen one&#39;s autonomy, but that the institutionalising of data gathering is exposing the user to the control of others and, thereby, control over one&#39;s self-disclosure is diminished. A case study of three self-tracking technologies (Fitbit, Runkeeper, and Dailymile) explicates this movement.</p><div class="ds-related-work--ctas"><a class="ds2-5-text-link ds2-5-text-link--inline js-tc-loswp--wsj-grid-card-download-pdf-modal js-login-button--5d537d4c"><span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">download</span><span class="ds2-5-text-link__content">Download free PDF</span></a><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
