y-sm ds-related-work--abstract hide-on-large">As in all media upheavals, the public debate regarding the quantified self movement, along with the practice of self-tracking, is being attended by emancipatory utopias. Hence self-tracking practices are often praised as extensions of individual self-determination, or on the other hand judged as another step toward neoliberal self-subjugation, and sometimes even seen in terms of cultural pessimism as a technological threat to humanity. Using this technology joins together with the wish to learn more about oneself or human beings in general through scientific analysis. However, these approaches disregard what is obvious to the study of media culture, that is, that using this technology means that it enters into the cognitive process. The following paper takes a look at this role of the media technologies primarily involved in tracking. This undertaking is flanked by online surveys conducted in the summer of 2015. Another intention, finally, is to look into the educational relevance of self-tracking practices.</p><div class="ds-related-work--ctas"><a class="ds2-5-text-link ds2-5-text-link--inline js-tc-loswp--wsj-grid-card-download-pdf-modal js-login-button--a361c874"><span class="material-symbols-outlined" style="font-size: 18px" translate="no">download</span><span class="ds2-5-text-link__content">Download free PDF</span></a><script>document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
